  canonical="/pesco-bill/"
  introContent={`
    <p>Peshawar Electric Supply Company (PESCO) supplies electricity to nearly 4.8 million consumers across the settled districts of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KPK) — Pakistan's northwestern province bordering Afghanistan. Established in 1998, PESCO is the primary electricity distributor for KPK's major cities including <strong>Peshawar</strong> (the provincial capital), <strong>Mardan</strong>, <strong>Swabi</strong>, <strong>Nowshera</strong>, <strong>Charsadda</strong>, <strong>Swat</strong>, <strong>Dir</strong>, <strong>Abbottabad</strong>, <strong>Mansehra</strong>, <strong>Haripur</strong>, <strong>Kohat</strong>, <strong>Bannu</strong>, and <strong>Dera Ismail Khan</strong>.</p>
    <p>PESCO's territory is geographically diverse — from the fertile Peshawar valley and Mardan's sugar cane fields to the mountainous Swat valley (Pakistan's tourist capital), the Hazara hills, and the tribal borderlands of Kohat and Bannu. This geographic diversity creates unique challenges for power distribution and load management. PESCO consumers in mountain areas like Swat and Abbottabad experience significantly different load shedding patterns than urban Peshawar consumers.</p>
    <p>PESCO's <strong>winter peak hours are 5:00 PM to 9:00 PM</strong> — one hour earlier than other DISCOs. This reflects KPK's earlier winter darkness due to its higher latitude and mountainous terrain. Always check the winter peak hours before running heavy appliances in November to March. Summer peak hours follow the national standard of 6:30 PM to 10:30 PM.</p>
    <p>To check your PESCO bill online, enter your <strong>14-digit PESCO reference number</strong> in the bill checker above. PESCO is operated under PEPCO and uses the same PITC server as all other WAPDA DISCOs — the same 14-digit reference number format applies. Note: for tribal areas of KPK, check <a href="/tesco-bill/">TESCO bill page</a> — tribal areas use TESCO, not PESCO.</p>
  
    <p>PakistanBill.online is <strong>Pakistan's only platform</strong> covering all 19 utility providers. Also check: <a href="/iesco-bill/">IESCO bill</a> for Islamabad | <a href="/tesco-bill/">TESCO bill</a> for Tribal Districts | <a href="/sngpl-bill/">SNGPL gas bill</a>. Use our <a href="/electricity-bill-calculator/">electricity bill calculator</a>, visit our <a href="/dashboard/">bill dashboard</a>, or read <a href="/blog/electricity-bill-calculator-guide/">how to calculate your electricity bill</a>. See our complete <a href="/peshawar/">Peshawar utility bills guide</a>.</p>
  `}
  howToSteps={[
    "Find your 14-digit PESCO reference number — printed in bold at the top of your PESCO bill. Both urban and rural KPK consumers use the same 14-digit format.",
    "Open the bill checker at the top of this page. Reference Number tab is selected by default.",
    "Enter your 14-digit PESCO reference number. Numbers only — no spaces or dashes.",
    "Click Check Bill. The tool connects to bill.pitc.com.pk/pescobill and fetches your bill.",
    "Your complete PESCO bill appears in 3 to 5 seconds with all charges and due date.",
    "Click Download PDF to save as PDF, or Print for an immediate paper copy."
  ]}
  billReadingTips={[
    "PESCO winter peak hours start at 5:00 PM — one hour earlier than other DISCOs. Running heavy appliances between 5 PM and 9 PM in winter costs more per unit for connections above 5kW.",
    "Swat, Abbottabad, and Mansehra consumers: mountain weather means heating loads in winter. Electric heaters add 200–400 units monthly. Consider gas heaters or wood stoves as cheaper alternatives for heating.",
    "KPK consumers near Afghanistan border areas: your connection may be PESCO or TESCO depending on your exact location. Check your bill heading — if it says PITC/PESCO, use this page. If it says TESCO, use our TESCO bill page.",
    "The Estimated tag on your PESCO bill means no actual meter reading was taken. This is common in difficult terrain areas of Swat, Dir, and Chitral. Request an actual reading to avoid large catch-up bills.",
    "PESCO has implemented smart metering in Peshawar city. Smart meter consumers receive automated readings monthly — if you have a smart meter, check your bill for the AMR or Smart Meter tag.",
  ]}
  savingTips={[
    "Use fans instead of AC in Swat, Abbottabad, Mansehra, and Chitral — KPK mountain areas have naturally cool summer temperatures. Most mountain-area consumers can avoid AC entirely and maintain Protected status.",
    "Peshawar valley consumers face hot summers. Set AC to 26°C and use fans simultaneously. Peshawar's dry heat is easier to cool than humid climates — proper ventilation helps significantly.",
    "For KPK agricultural consumers using PESCO for tube wells: run pumps during morning hours (7 AM to 12 PM) — off-peak, low-demand period when per-unit costs are lower.",
    "Install solar panels for Swat, Chitral, and Dir — KPK mountain areas receive excellent solar irradiance with clear skies. Net metering is available under NEPRA's prosumer framework.",
    "Avoid electric heaters in KPK winters. A 2kW electric room heater running 6 hours daily adds approximately 360 units per month — pushing Protected consumers firmly into Unprotected territory.",
  ]}
